# Pre-Commit / Pre-Push Checklist

Before running `git commit` or `git push`, verify the following files are in sync with the current tool count and new tools added.

## When a new tool is added to `lib/tools.ts`

1. **`README.md`** — add the new tool under the correct category section. Do not claim all tools are client-side/backend-free — some tools (e.g. URL Shortener) use a backend; keep the intro wording accurate ("Most tools run 100% client-side... A few use a lightweight backend").

2. **`public/llms.txt`** — add the new tool under the correct category section with its slug path. This file is manually maintained and does NOT auto-sync.

3. **`app/sitemap.ts`** — bump `LAST_MODIFIED` to today's date (`YYYY-MM-DD`). This is the only part of the sitemap that requires manual updates; the URL list auto-syncs from `tools`.

4. **`app/tools/[slug]/ToolPageClient.tsx`** — register the new tool slug in `TOOL_MAP` with a `next/dynamic` import.

## Files that auto-sync (no manual update needed)

- `app/sitemap.ts` URL list — auto-maps over `tools`
- `app/page.tsx` FAQ answer — uses `tools.length`
- `app/about/page.tsx` OG description — uses `tools.length`
- `components/HomepageClient.tsx` hero copy — uses `tools.length`
- Homepage category filter and ⌘K command palette — auto-derive from `CATEGORY_ORDER` / `tools`

## When installing a new npm dependency

Always run `npx pnpm@10 install` (NOT just `npm install`) after adding any package. Vercel uses pnpm for production builds and checks `pnpm-lock.yaml` with `--frozen-lockfile`. If only `package-lock.json` is updated, the Vercel build will fail with `ERR_PNPM_OUTDATED_LOCKFILE`.

```bash
# Correct workflow for new dependencies
npm install some-package          # installs and updates package-lock.json
npx pnpm@10 install               # syncs pnpm-lock.yaml — MUST do this too
git add package.json package-lock.json pnpm-lock.yaml
```

## Quick sanity check before committing

```bash
# Count tool bullets within the "## Tools" section of README.md only
# (scoped between "## Tools" and "## Stack" — a bare grep over the whole
# file also matches unrelated bullets, e.g. in the Stack section)
sed -n '/^## Tools/,/^## Stack/p' README.md | grep -c "^- "
# Count tool entries in lib/tools.ts — should match the number above
grep -c "    slug:" lib/tools.ts
```
